    "discriminators": [
     "Ice is brittle and stiff: a fracture is a very fast, very high-crest, HIGH-centroid crack, often followed by a short scatter of shards (the tail). Brightness and crest are what mark 'brittle'.",
     "Against ICE-IMPACT: UCS is explicit — IMPACT is ice hitting something WITHOUT breaking. A break adds fracture debris (a burst of secondary onsets after the transient) and a brighter, more inharmonic spectrum. The post-transient onset_rate_per_second is the test.",
     "Against ICE-CRASH & DEBRIS: UCS routes SINGULAR or isolated breaks here and LARGE crashes with sustained debris there. Duration and debris density separate them, not timbre.",
     "Against SNOW-CRASH & DEBRIS: snow is the opposite material — absorptive, dark, dead. Ice is bright and ringing. spectral_centroid_hz separates them by an octave or more.",
     "Against GLASS-BREAK: acoustically near-identical brittle fracture. Semantic; the filename decides."
    ],
    "confusable_with": [
