    "discriminators": [
     "Sustained contact, not an event: a scrape, squeak or creak holds energy for hundreds of ms with a soft attack and a LOW crest_factor. That is what separates all of ICE-FRICTION from ICE-IMPACT and ICE-BREAK, which are transient-dominated with crest_factor three times higher.",
     "Unstable by nature — stick-slip makes the centroid wander, so spectral_centroid_deviation_hz and spectral_flux run high while stationarity stays middling.",
     "Bright: ice scrapes are high-centroid, and UCS notes they often read as metallic. Squeaks can go strongly tonal, hence the elevated inharmonicity.",
     "Against SNOW-FRICTION: same morphology, opposite material. Snow is a soft granular crunch — darker, denser, and with no ring or squeal. This is the material axis, and it is real but subtle.",
     "Against ICE-MOVEMENT: MOVEMENT is a rattle or slide of discrete pieces (resolvable onsets); FRICTION is continuous surface contact."
