    "discriminators": [
     "The one pitched member of the ICE family: high harmonicity, very low spectral_flatness. Tonality alone separates it cleanly from every other ICE subcategory, which are all noise or transients.",
     "The 'ice ping on a frozen lake' is a DISPERSIVE wave in a floating plate: high frequencies travel faster, so the ping arrives as a descending chirp. Hence the negative pitch_slope_semitones_per_second prior — a genuinely diagnostic and unusual cue, though the wide deviation admits plain rings.",
     "Inharmonicity stays moderate: an ice plate's modes are stretched, not a clean harmonic series. This distinguishes it from a musical tone.",
     "Against ICE-IMPACT: an impact is a broadband click; TONAL rings with a definite pitch and a long decay_time_seconds_60db.",
     "UCS notes this is rare. Prefer ICE-IMPACT or ICE-BREAK unless harmonicity is genuinely high."
    ],
